SENATE JOINT RESOLUTION 896
By Johnson
A RESOLUTION to honor Lt. Governor Randy McNally, Speaker
of the Senate, for his exemplary service to this
General Assembly and the State of Tennessee.
WHEREAS, we have the rare privilege to specially recognize and honor one of the most
dedicated, most effective, and longest-serving elected officials this State has ever produced,
namely one James Rand "Randy" McNally III of Oak Ridge; and
WHEREAS, having proudly represented his fellow citizens at the State Capitol for forty-
eight years, from the 91st through the 114th General Assemblies, Lt. Governor Randy McNally
has announced his retirement from the Senate at the adjournment sine die of the 2026 session,
having served as a towering example for public service; and
WHEREAS, born on January 30, 1944, in Dedham, Massachusetts, Lt. Governor Randy
McNally attended Oak Ridge High School; he received his Bachelor of Science degree from
Memphis State University in 1967 and graduated from the University of Tennessee College of
Pharmacy in 1969; and
WHEREAS, enjoying a distinguished career in health care, Lt. Governor McNally began
working as a hospital pharmacist at Methodist Medical Center in Oak Ridge in 1978 and served
in that capacity for more than four decades before taking his well-deserved retirement; and
WHEREAS, offering himself for service in Nashville, Randy McNally won election to the
legislature in November 1978, when the good people of House District 33, then composed of
Anderson and Roane counties, evinced their great faith in the political and governmental
capabilities of the young man from Oak Ridge by electing him as their State Representative;
and
WHEREAS, as a member of the House of Representatives, Lt. Governor McNally
rendered sterling service as a member of the Conservation and Environment Committee, the
SJR0896
014263
- 1 -

Labor and Consumer Affairs Committee, the Education Committee, and the Finance, Ways, and
Means Committee and as the Republican Caucus Floor Leader of the 93rd and 94th General
Assemblies; and
WHEREAS, in November 1986, Lt. Governor McNally won election to the Senate to
represent the good people of Senate District 5, which included Anderson, Loudon, Monroe, and
part of Knox counties; and
WHEREAS, prior to becoming Speaker of the Senate, Lt. Governor McNally ably served
tenures as chair of the Senate Education Committee, chair and vice chair of the Senate
Finance, Ways and Means Committee, chair of the Senate Finance, Ways and Means Tax
Subcommittee, chair of the Joint Council on Pensions and Insurance, vice chair of the Senate
Rules Committee, and member of the Senate General Welfare Committee, the Joint Select
Oversight Committee on Education, the Joint Business Tax Committee, the Joint Lottery
Oversight Committee, the Joint Fiscal Review Committee, and the Joint Fiscal Review Contract
Services Subcommittee; and
WHEREAS, in January 2017, Randy McNally was formally elected Speaker of the
Senate for the 110th General Assembly and has served with distinction in that role since that
time, winning reelection to the speakership for the 111th, 112th, 113th, and 114th General
Assemblies; and
WHEREAS, during his illustrious tenure in the General Assembly, Randy McNally has
not only been a faithful servant of his district, he has also demonstrated the vision and fortitude
necessary to move Tennessee forward as a State; and
WHEREAS, a gentleman who truly appreciates the responsibilities, as well as the
privileges, of citizenship, Lt. Governor McNally has generously donated his time and energies to
many community, civic, professional, and governmental organizations, including the Chamber of
Commerce, the Red Cross, Oak Ridge Girls Club, Community Services for Exceptional Citizens,
- 2 - 014263

Big Brother-Big Sister of Oak Ridge, the Tennessee Pharmaceutical Association, Rotary Club,
Elder Citizens Advisory Board, Anderson County American Cancer Society, Anderson County
Health Council, and the Advisory Board of Tennessee Donor Services; and
WHEREAS, Randy McNally has certainly been no stranger to awards and accolades
during his distinguished career; he was named the Oak Ridge Jaycees Young Man of the Year
in 1977, the Republican Legislator of the Year in 1990, MADD Outstanding Legislator, Sertoma
Man of the Year in 1991, and Junior Leagues of Tennessee Legislator of the Year in 2005; and
WHEREAS, he received the Bill Bates Award in 1994, the Common Cause "Bird Dog"
Award in 1994, the Distinguished Service Award from the University of Tennessee College of
Pharmacy in 1996, the Distinguished Service Award from the American Council on Alcohol
Programs in 1994, the Tennessee Organization of School Superintendents Legislative Award in
2004, the Tennessee School Boards Association Legislative Award in 2004, the Rotary
Vocational Service Award in 2001, the CASA President's Award in 2012, the Legislative Hero
Award from the Tennessee Association of Mental Health Organizations in 2012, the TBI
Distinguished Award in 2012, the Small Business Guardian of Small Business Award in 2012,
and the Distinguished Legislative Service Award from the Tennessee Association of Accessing
Officers, and he was named a Paul Harris Fellow by Rotary International in 1996; and
WHEREAS, the patriarch of a loving family, he treasures the support and companionship
of his wife, Jan; their two children, Melissa and Maggie; and their three grandchildren, Haley,
Morgan, and Trent; and
WHEREAS, his departure from this body will truly mark the end of an era in the history of
the General Assembly, as Lt. Governor McNally's retirement will create a void that will not be
easily filled; his considerable talents and presence will be sorely missed by the membership of
this body, the legislative staff, and the good people of Senate District 5; and
- 3 - 014263

WHEREAS, this General Assembly is deeply saddened to bid farewell to our friend and
colleague Lt. Governor Randy McNally; now, therefore,
BE IT RESOLVED BY THE SENATE OF THE ONE HUNDRED FOURTEENTH
GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF THE STATE OF TENNESSEE, THE HOUSE OF
REPRESENTATIVES CONCURRING, that we honor and commend Lt. Governor Randy
McNally for his forty-eight years of distinguished service as a member of this General Assembly
and his outstanding tenure as Speaker of the Senate and wish him all the best as he continues
his remarkable life's journey.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that an appropriate copy of this resolution be prepared
for presentation with this final clause omitted from such copy and upon proper request made to
the appropriate clerk, the language appearing immediately following the State seal appear
without House or Senate designation.
- 4 - 014263

